STAY-AT-HOME MISSOURI!
To WIN this battle against COVID-19, it is going to take EACH ONE OF US doing our part.

This is not about any one individual person. 

This is about our families, friends, and neighbors. This is about the ENTIRE state of Missouri.

Therefore, my order will provide a clear framework to allow businesses to operate, but they will have to follow social distancing measures.

By tightening the exemptions that led to an unintended funnel effect, my order goes further than ANY directive in the state.
Medical experts have told us is that some essential businesses have become hotbeds for transmission as people flock to those locations and risk spreading the virus even further.

Many orders were put into place early on in other states and many cities without thinking about the un-intended consequences. 

Hundreds of businesses were declared essential and THOUSANDS were declared non-essential.

Over one hundred THOUSAND people have filed for unemployment, and I‚Äôm sure they all would tell you they thought their jobs were essential.

Their spouses, families, and everyone who depends on them, thought their jobs were essential.

This power is something I think should be rare for government to ever take advantage of ‚Ä¶ and for one person to make the decision for 6 million Missourians without due process, jeopardizing their liberties.

It is not just about encouraging people to stay at home. 

It is about having the power as Governor to pick winners and losers ‚Ä¶ and whether I feel it is appropriate for me to use that power by determining who is essential and who is not.

This state means so much to me. There are 6 million of us that call Missouri home. 

We live in small towns and large cities, and our diversity is one of the greatest advantages we have as a state.

‚óã All individuals in the State of Missouri shall avoid social gatherings of more than ten (10) people.

These monies will be paid retroactively for claims filed on or after March 29 after the federal government issues guidance and releases those funds.

We just received news that since Missouri signed an agreement with the U.S. Department of Labor on Saturday, the $600 dollar supplement for those that are unemployed will be effective this week for those filing for unemployment payment.
Many people are also asking questions about the recently passed federal legislation regarding unemployment for the self-employed and the $600 supplement.
We have prioritized unemployment claims, and over 90 percent of people have been able to file their claims online through U-Interact, which has experienced only one two-hour period of down time.

Missourians need to realize that unemployment claims are at un-imagined historic highs. @MOLabor is receiving over 100,000 calls each day. For the week ending March 28, the Department reported over 104,000 initial unemployment claims.
I want to address some recent concerns regarding unemployment claims. We are very aware of the fact that people are struggling to get through to the Department of Labor (@MOLabor).

We cannot do this alone, and we cannot thank you all enough for your efforts during this challenging time. A tremendous amount of work has already been accomplished  and we will continue to exhaust ALL OPTIONS until Missouri overcomes and fully recovers from the COVID-19 crisis!

I want Missourians to know that we ARE working extremely hard for the people of this state.

Not just government, but our doctors, nurses, public health professionals, law enforcement, first responders, truck drivers, grocery store workers & ALL Missourians on the frontlines.
We have mobilized the @Missouri_NG  to further assist our efforts and they are working to identify potential Alternate Care Sites, if needed, around the state.

We have approved the purchase of tens of millions of dollars worth of PPE and are working rapidly each day to get these shipments out. 

We have requested, and been approved for, a federal major disaster declaration in the state of Missouri.
In addition to six Executive Orders, we have now waived or suspended 276 state statutes and regulations.

Today, I signed our SIXTH Executive Order in response to COVID-19. 

This EO suspends late penalties for concealed carry license renewals. This EO not only promotes public health and social distancing, but also frees up local law enforcement officers from administrative tasks.

Day in and day out, we are working around the clock to respond and adapt to COVID-19 in every way possible. 

I am in CONSTANT communication with leaders and medical experts across the state on a daily basis.

The emergency funding Missouri is receiving for the COVID-19 pandemic is allotted to the state based on census population data. In order to be adequately funded, Missouri must first be adequately counted.
April 1st is Census Day. These are challenging times, and while taking part in the 2020 Census may not currently be at the top of your list, responses to the 2020 Census are more important than ever.
So for the sake of ALL Missourians, be smart, be responsible, and STAY HOME.
We need to get rid of the mentality that people are ‚Äústuck‚Äù at  home. You are SAFE at home.
No matter where you live or how old you are, EVERYONE should be staying home as much as possible. By not following these orders, you are putting yourself and everyone around you at risk.

As I have said many times, the COVID-19 situation changes EVERY DAY. Every day, we are constantly re-evaluating and looking at all possible options.
 
But again, the most important step anyone can take right now is STAYING HOME.

These are not easy decisions, but just as families and businesses have to balance their budgets and make hard decisions, we are doing the same. This is the right thing to do to make sure our budget is balanced and we are financially prepared to deal with the impacts of COVID-19.

Of the $180 million, I assure you these restrictions are absolutely necessary and include funding for several departments ‚Äì many of which are priorities of my own administration. In addition, the Judiciary & Secretary of State have worked to identify savings in their own budgets.
In addition to the $180 million we‚Äôre restricting in the budget, we are hopeful we may be able to use an additional $315 million dollars in federal funding this year to help with the shortfall.
To ensure our budget is balanced and we have the funds to combat COVID-19 going forward, we are planning to restrict $180 million dollars in spending.

Between now and June 31st, we are estimating an over $500 million shortfall.
 
We have had to take a hard look at our budget and make some very difficult decisions.
While we still do not know the true impact of COVID-19 on the economy, we do know that we have to act NOW.

When we began this fiscal year, we anticipated economic growth, and we had based our budget on that growth. COVID-19 has had serious impacts on our anticipated economic growth, and now we are expecting significant revenue declines.

However, the impact of COVID-19 has already been hard felt in our economy.
 
More people are staying home. Businesses operations have been limited, many people have lost their jobs, and state revenues are down.
The General Assembly has also shown great restraint and leadership in passing conservative budgets, and by working together, we have been able to ensure that our state is financially sound.

Last year, we were able to leave $100 million dollars on the bottom line in order to respond to any unexpected revenue declines.
 
We also proposed to do the same for next year, ensuring
another year of responsible state budgeting and savings.

Up until this point in my administration, we have been very fortunate to have a booming economy with record low unemployment & high wage growth.
 
Incomes have gone up, & taxes have gone down.
We have, at many times, had more jobs available than we have had people to fill them.
As I said yesterday, COVID-19 is having a serious impact not only on public health, but also our economy.
